  "texts": [
    "After providing a brief overview of how deepfakes threaten 7 Page 2 of 19 knowledge, I argue that automated detection technologies cannot fully address these threats.",
    "Then, I argue that reliance on deepfake detectors, more so than reliance on other forms of artificial intelligence, threatens epistemic autonomy.",
    "This threat to epistemic autonomy is especially dire, as automated deepfake detectors may pick up on signs of inauthenticity that are imperceptible to humans, thus generating ineliminable tensions between the detector's verdicts and what seems perceptually to be the case.",
    "In this way, technological solutions to the problem of deepfakes threaten to supplant reliance on individuals' own senses, while also undermining trust in those senses.",
    "Before considering the prospects for technological solutions to the problem of deepfakes, it is necessary, first, to establish a better understanding of that problem."
  ],
